<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1925-10-24T00:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1925-10-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="708" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d708">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A 4 e/426: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Delegation</gloss>
                                to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1925-10-24T13:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">October 24,
                                        1925—1 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received October 24—4
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>464. My 388, Sept. 10, 11 a.m. Mandate of October 22 appoints Shen
                            Jui-lin, Minister for Foreign Affairs, W. W. Yen, C. T. Wang, Huang Fu,
                            Alfred Sze<note n="74" xml:id="d708fn74">Sao-Ke Alfred Sze, Chinese
                                Minister at Washington, did not attend the Conference.</note> and
                            Admiral Tsai Tink-kan as delegates with full powers to the Customs
                            Conference.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Am</hi>[<hi rend="smallcaps">erican</hi>] <hi rend="smallcaps">Tar</hi>[<hi rend="smallcaps">iff</hi>] <hi rend="smallcaps">Del</hi>[<hi rend="smallcaps">egation</hi>]</signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>